{"query": "How does the evidence for using acoustically reflective materials on fishing gear compare to attaching acoustically reflective objects for reducing marine mammal entanglement?", "summary": "The evidence shows that acoustically reflective fishing gear materials have more consistent positive results compared to attached acoustically reflective objects. For acoustically reflective materials (action 2807), five studies showed mixed but more encouraging results: three controlled studies found reduced entanglements of harbour porpoises in nets made from iron-oxide or barium sulfate materials, while two studies found no effect on dolphin entanglements. Behavior studies showed some reduction in echolocation clicks by harbour porpoises at barium sulfate nets, though approach distances remained similar to conventional nets.

In contrast, attached acoustically reflective objects (action 2806) showed consistently negative results across two studies: one controlled study found metallic bead chains attached to fishing nets did not reduce dolphin entanglements, and another controlled study found acrylic beads attached next to fishing hooks did not reduce sperm whale predation on fish catches.

The evidence base is also notably different: acoustically reflective materials were tested in five studies across multiple regions (Canada, Denmark, Argentina), while attached objects were only tested in two studies (Australia, Alaska). This suggests more research support exists for investigating acoustically reflective materials as a potential mitigation strategy.", "action_ids": ["2806", "2807", "2808", "2820"]}

