tools_called.args:
{"query": "What is the evidence for interventions that directly manage individual mammals to boost threatened populations?", "summary": "Evidence shows several direct management interventions can boost threatened mammal populations. Translocation of marine and freshwater mammals has been successful, with studies showing 50-83% survival rates for translocated Hawaiian monk seal pups, and over 25% of translocated seals reproduced after release (Action ID: 2930). Captive breeding and release programs show mixed results - while two of three released Antillean manatees and two of 14 Florida manatees survived at least one year (Action ID: 2933), primates born and reared in cages had poor survival outcomes compared to wild-born individuals (Action ID: 1594), though those raised in free-ranging environments had better outcomes (Action ID: 1596).

Disease treatment interventions show potential, with medical treatment healing most infected mouflons against foot rot disease (Action ID: 2581). Providing supplementary food has demonstrated positive effects on reproduction and survival across multiple studies, increasing breeding proportions in striped mice, arctic fox litters, and prairie vole litter sizes, while also improving survival rates for mule deer, bank voles, and eastern cottontail rabbits (Action ID: 2367). Supplementary feeding during translocation also improved survival and reproductive success for various species including black-tailed prairie dogs, red squirrels, and Eurasian badgers (Action ID: 2470).

Removing problematic individuals can benefit populations - after removing aggressive male Hawaiian monk seals, adult female survival increased and fewer females were injured (Action ID: 2929). Training mammals to avoid predators showed limited success, with trained greater bilbies not showing increased post-release survival despite some behavioral changes (Action ID: 2580).", "action_ids": ["2930", "2933", "1594", "1596", "2581", "2367", "2470", "2929", "2580"]}

