{
  "query": "What are the potential negative impacts associated with using acoustic deterrent devices for marine mammal conservation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, acoustic deterrent devices can have several negative impacts on marine mammals. Studies show that these devices cause significant behavioral changes and habitat displacement. Specifically, research on using acoustic devices to deter marine and freshwater mammals from an area at wind farm construction sites and pelagic sites found reduced activity and sightings of harbour porpoises at distances of 1\u201318 km from the devices. A study in Faxafl\u00f3i Bay found that when acoustic devices were deployed, minke whales exhibited stress responses by swimming away from the device, increasing their swimming speed, and swimming more directly. These forced behavioral modifications and habitat exclusion represent negative impacts on marine mammal populations by disrupting their natural behavior patterns and potentially displacing them from critical feeding or breeding areas.",
  "action_ids": [
    "2896"
  ]
}

