{
  "query": "What are the documented behavioral effects on marine mammals of implementing regulations for vessel operations during tourism activities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Four studies documented the behavioral effects on marine mammals from implementing vessel operation regulations during tourism activities. Two controlled studies in the North Atlantic Ocean (Azores) and South Pacific Ocean (Australia) found that when whale-watching vessels followed approach regulations, fewer sperm whales and humpback whale pods changed their behaviors (such as swimming speed, aerial displays) or avoided the vessels compared to when regulations were not followed, but direction of movement and diving patterns or diving behaviors did not differ. One replicated, controlled study in the Canan\u00e9ia estuary (Brazil) found that when tour boats followed approach regulations, fewer Guiana dolphins displayed negative behaviors such as moving away, diving, or groups separating. One study in the Bass Strait (Australia) found that when boats approached a seal colony to 75 m, more seals remained on shore than when boats approached to 25 m. No studies were found that directly evaluated the effects of developing and implementing general vessel regulations around mammals, setting minimum approach distances, or using detection systems to alter vessel operations.",
