{
  "action_id": "283",
  "action_title": "Set longlines at night to reduce seabird bycatch",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nSix out of eight studies from fisheries around the world found lower rates of seabird bycatch on longlines set at night, compared with during the day, or with previously collected data. However, effects seemed to depend on the species caught.\nTwo studies found higher rates of bycatch on night-set longlines, due to high numbers of white-chinned petrels Procellaria aequinoctialis or northern fulmars Fulmarus glacialis being caught at night."
}

{
  "action_id": "288",
  "action_title": "Set lines underwater to reduce seabird bycatch",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nFour replicated and controlled studies and a literature review in Norway, South Africa and the North Pacific found reductions in northern fulmar Fulmarus glacialis, albatross and petrel bycatch rates when using an underwater setting funnel. Although one found a disproportionate number of albatross were caught during day line setting.\nA replicated and controlled study found that underwater setting increased attack rates of shearwaters Puffinus spp. on longlines and did not reduce bycatch."
}

{
  "action_id": "284",
  "action_title": "Turn deck lights off during night-time setting of longlines to reduce bycatch",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nA single replicated and controlled study in the South Atlantic found significantly lower bycatch rates when deck lights were turned off during line setting at night."
}

{
