{"query": "Based on the available evidence, what are the most beneficial actions for reducing human-wildlife conflict at wild fisheries?", "summary": "Based on the available evidence, the most beneficial actions for reducing human-wildlife conflict at wild fisheries include several approaches for different wildlife groups. For marine mammals, installing exclusion and escape devices on fishing nets reduced entanglements of Antarctic fur seals and common bottlenose dolphins (actions 2823, 2808). Using acoustic devices on fishing gear was effective in 12 of 16 studies, reducing encounters with and damage from harbour porpoises, common bottlenose dolphins, and seals (action 2808). Modifying fishing pots and traps with wire grids or steel bars reduced seal access and damage to salmon catches (action 2822). Establishing handling and release protocols for captured mammals resulted in lower mortality of short-beaked common dolphins (action 2829).

For seabirds, using streamer lines on longlines showed strong evidence for reducing bycatch across multiple studies, with the effect enhanced when multiple streamer lines were used (action 285). Setting longlines at night reduced bycatch rates in six of eight studies (action 283). Setting lines underwater through specialized funnels reduced bycatch of northern fulmars, albatross and petrels (action 288). Releasing offal overboard during line setting significantly reduced attacks and captures of albatross and petrels (action 299). However, one study found that barriers installed at wild fisheries did not effectively deter harbour seals from feeding on salmon (action 2824).

The effectiveness of these actions varies by species, with some interventions working better for certain wildlife groups than others.", "action_ids": ["2823", "2808", "2822", "2829", "285", "283", "288", "299", "2824"]}
